SIMPLE: fulcrum
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fulcrum
<hw>Ful"crum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L.
<plw>Fulcra</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>Fulcrums</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., bedpost, fr. <ets>fulcire</ets> to
prop.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A prop or support.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>That by which a lever is
sustained, or about which it turns in lifting or moving a
body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An accessory organ such as a
tendril, stipule, spine, and the like.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The horny inferior
surface of the lingua of certain insects.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of
the small, spiniform scales found on the front edge of the dorsal and
caudal fins of many ganoid fishes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The connective tissue supporting
the framework of the retina of the eye.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fulfill</ent>⟦br⟧
